I am working with Tony and John to schedule some talks on data ethics and data privacy. If you have any thoughts that pertain to this please let me know. ^^^ <@U1KRB11QC> I thought that the technology and application methods presented by Red Ventures highlighted a number of significant concerns in this area.

I'm personally very confused by all the talk about the supposed ethics questions regarding Red Ventures.  Apparently people think it's unethical to outsource your call center?  So yeah I guess it's good we're having that talk.

It's not unethical to outsource, it's unethical to use demographic information to decide on whether someone receives service or not. I.e. low income callers might get dropped in high volume periods in favor of high income callers.

<@U1L1D4WG7> that is something that is also on my list. It seems to me there is a bit of grey area in this space. I'm curious where we draw the line. Data science is in its infancy and currently doesn't have any ethical oversight organizations like other industries. It also seems like most of the times these organizations are set up when bad things happen and as data scientists we should aim to be better than that
well put <@U1KRB11QC>

Hahaha <@U1KRLV1CG> it makes a clicking sound when I turn it on, anyone know what that may mean? Google isn't really helping
Clicking means that it doesn't have enough energy in the battery to turnover, but having lights and it still not turning over is more likely than not an alternator problem
Jumping it will help momentarily but the dead alternator will drain the battery pretty quickly because it's not able to recharge it
<@U1KRB11QC> I concur
depends on how bright the lights are. You can have dim lights but still not enough energy to turn over, particularly in cold weather.
if you can jump it and get it to start just make sure you drive it around for at least 20 mins
You could have someone jump you and then have them follow you. If it is the alternator your car will turn off pretty quickly when driving
